content.description: Sit start on really solid patinas. Pull up, bump right hand to pinch intermediate, get hands into anything on the crack. Good feet & some hand/finger jams above
content.location: On the same boulder as Crackers. Facing the boulder, it's on the left side.

content.description:
Sit-start on a sloper (thumb-catch on sloper somewhere, crimp is right on the edge of the sloper). Decent foot ledge on the bottom near the ground. Pull up, bump left to a decent dish directly above. Crank a bit up, bump out left to a really jagged patina slot. Heel hook on start, bump up right to another patina and get yourself over the boulder.

It's REALLY sharp. Be careful.
content.location: The boulder directly to the right of Crackers. Has an entire surface covered in sun-baked patinas.

content.description:
Sit start on crimpy holds on right-side of boulder. Pull up into a slope-y hold, get a high right-foot onto the start and push up to the top (slopers everywhere, with a single micro-crimp somewhere).

Named after a very kind gentleman that towed my car out of some snow in Dairy Canyon on my first trip out to Joe's.
content.location: Boulder directly across from Crackers & Shooter. Sitting down @ the start should point you towards the road.

content.description: Sit start around the right-side of Crackers. Right-hand in the biggest slot, left hand on slope-y crimp facing right. Pull and stand up, left-gaston into the Jug start of Crackers

Stand start on big jug. Stand up, find a decent sloper, go straight to the top.

Named after a cat.
content.location:
Right off the road where 401 meets the 404, there should be a pile of rocks that you can walk right in-between of. It should be the first boulder on the right-side.

As of writing this, has "crackers" written in chalk
